    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <head>157. Memorandum for the President’s File by Secretary of the Treasury
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP1">Shultz</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d157fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, White House
                        Special Files, Staff Member &amp; Office Files, President’s Office Files,
                        Box 91, President’s Meeting File, Memoranda for the President’s File,
                        Beginning Feb 4 (1973). No classification marking. The meeting took place in
                        the Oval Office. The President met with <persName corresp="#p_SGP1"
                            >Shultz</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_EJ1">Ehrlichman</persName>
                        from 3:15 to 3:44 p.m., at which time <persName corresp="#p_MW1"
                            >Mills</persName> entered the room and <persName corresp="#p_EJ1"
                            >Ehrlichman</persName> left. The President then met with <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP1">Shultz</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MW1"
                            >Mills</persName> from 3:44 to 5:11 p.m. (Ibid., White House Central
                        Files, President’s Daily Diary)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1973-02-07">February 7, 1973</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Meeting of Wednesday, February 7, 1973, 3:30 p.m. with the President,
                        Congressman <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Wilbur D. Mills</persName> and
                        Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SGP1">Shultz</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1)</label>
                    <item>The President explored <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName>’
                        interest in having the President appear some time at Hendrix College
                            (<persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName>’ alma mater) and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> assured him he would be welcome at any
                        time. <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> noted the interest at the
                        college in training people for careers involving work abroad.</item>
                    <label>2)</label>
                    <item>The President outlined to <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> his
                        hope for a personal relationship that would be characterized by candid
                        discussion between the two of them. The President expressed his desire to
                        explore problems in advance (tax proposals for example) so that the
                        President’s proposals would be in the ballpark.</item>
                    <label>3)</label>
                    <item>The following points on the trade bill were made: <list>
                            <label>a)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> notes <gloss
                                    target="#t_MFN1">MFN</gloss> problem with Russia and suggests
                                that the President use Congressional attitudes as a bargaining
                                lever.</item>
                            <label>b)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> expressed view that
                                protectionist pressures are strong and therefore we must be wary in
                                introducing a trade bill.</item>
                            <label>c)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> suggests the President
                                impose a surcharge to stop the flood of imports, with a declining
                                percentage over three years: 15 percent–10 percent–5 percent.</item>
                            <label>d)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> commented on pension
                                legislation allied to the trade bill and suggested provision for a
                                pooling arrangement among contractors in an area.</item>
                            <label>e)</label>
                            <item>The President expressed the view that Generalized Preferences
                                should be drawn in a manner that favors Latin America and <persName
                                    corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> agreed.</item>
                            <label>f)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> welcomed the
                                consultation but said the President must do what he thinks is right
                                than seek endlessly for a consensus.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>4)</label>
                    <item>The following points were made on taxes: <list>
                            <label>a)</label>
                            <item>The President stated his commitment to relief of the property tax
                                on the elderly and of the burden of tuition to private education.
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> agreed.</item>
                            <pb facs="0633" n="602" xml:id="pg_602"/>
                            <label>b)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MW1">Mills</persName> expressed his desire to
                                get the Government out of the position where it takes more than 50
                                percent of any person’s income and allied this to his desire to
                                block conversion of income into capital gains. He would also apply
                                his 50 percent rule to estate and gift taxes. His proposed method of
                                achieving these goals seemed obscure to me.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>5)</label>
                    <item>The meeting was most cordial in tone.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">George P.Shultz</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
